# Testing Conventions

## Framework
- Use pytest-django as test runner
- Use factory_boy for model fixtures (not Django fixtures)
- Use faker for generating realistic test data
- Prefix test files with `test_` (e.g., test_orders.py)
- Prefix test functions with `test_` (e.g., test_create_order)

## Factory Patterns
```python
# Example factory
class CustomerFactory(factory.django.DjangoModelFactory):
    class Meta:
        model = "customers.Customer"

    phone = factory.Sequence(lambda n: f"+7900{n:07d}")
    full_name = factory.Faker("name", locale="ru_RU")
    email = factory.Faker("email")
```

## Test Structure
- Arrange → Act → Assert pattern
- One assertion focus per test (can have multiple asserts for one concept)
- Use `@pytest.mark.django_db` for database tests
- Use `@pytest.fixture` for shared setup
- Group related tests in classes: `class TestOrderCreation:`

## What to Test
- Model validation and constraints
- Status transitions (valid and invalid)
- FIFO deduction logic (critical business logic)
- Selling price calculation
- API endpoint responses (status codes, payloads)
- Permission checks (who can access what)
- Celery task execution (use `celery.contrib.pytest`)

## Coverage Requirements
- Minimum 80% coverage on business logic (inventory, orders)
- 100% coverage on FIFO deduction and price calculation
- All status transitions must have positive and negative tests

## Naming Convention
```
test_{what}_{scenario}_{expected_result}
```
Example: `test_deduct_fifo_insufficient_stock_raises_error`

## Performance
- Use `pytest-xdist` for parallel test execution
- Keep tests fast: mock external APIs (WhatsApp, Google Maps, payment)
- Use `@pytest.mark.slow` for integration tests
